First, we need to concatenate the books of Harry Potter.

hp_books <- c(
  "philosophers_stone", 
  "chamber_of_secrets",
  "prisoner_of_azkaban", 
  "goblet_of_fire",
  "order_of_the_phoenix", 
  "half_blood_prince",
  "deathly_hallows"
)

Now, we tokenize them and finally we have 3 variables(book, chapter and word), which we essentially need it to develop and perform them later in order to create different analysis.

# combine books into a list
hp_words <- list(
  philosophers_stone,
  chamber_of_secrets,
  prisoner_of_azkaban,
  goblet_of_fire,
  order_of_the_phoenix,
  half_blood_prince,
  deathly_hallows
) |> 
  # name each list element
  set_names(hp_books) |> 
   #then, we convert each book to a data frame and merge it into a single data frame
  map_df(as_tibble, .id = "book") |> 
  #with factor we predefined levels ensures that the order of the levels to HP bools, taking more control and accuracy
  mutate(book = factor(book, levels = hp_books)) |> 
  # remove empty chapters
  drop_na(value) |> 
  # create a chapter id column
  group_by(book)  |> 
  mutate(chapter = row_number(book))  |> 
  ungroup()  |> 
  # tokenize the data frame
  unnest_tokens(word, value)

Frequency analysis

In all books, we can obtain the word frequency(WF). At first, we see that Harry is the most repeated word. But, we have another word in this top 15 which is Harry’s. Therefore, we unite them because we need to analyze the real impact of Harry in this project.

We do the same when we see the word Potter. With this code, we can add Potter to Harry when Potter is not preceded by Harry. Now, we count 3 ways that characters refers to Harry without putting at risk his over- or -underdimensioning.

hp_words_processed <- hp_words %>%
  mutate(word = gsub("harry's", "harry", word)) |> 
  mutate(word = gsub("(?<!\\bharry\\s)\\bpotter\\b", "harry", word, ignore.case = TRUE, perl = TRUE))
HP_all <- hp_words_processed  |> 
  # Remove stop words
  anti_join(stop_words)  |>  
  # Count the number of appearances
  count(word, sort = TRUE)  |> 
  # Select the top 20 word
  slice_max(order_by = n, n = 20)  |> 
  # Reordenar palabras por número de menciones
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n))
## Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
  # Crear el gráfico con la palabra (x) y el número de menciones (y)
  ggplot(HP_all, aes(y = reorder(word, n), x = n)) +
  geom_col(fill = "skyblue", color = "white") +
  labs(
    title = "Most frequent words in all HP books",
    x = NULL,
    y = "Word Count"
  ) +
  theme_dark() +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid = element_blank())

In Harry Potter’s books, the most repeated words are those referring to the main charaters like Harry, Ron, Hermione and Dumbledore who are the saviors of this story.

We also have professor, which is a word needed to show respect every time we hear about a teacher of the Academy. We also have wand referring to the magic of this world and dark, referring to the evil that comes.

HP_counts <- hp_words_processed %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
  count(book, word) %>%
  group_by(book) %>%

In the end, Harry needed a community to defeat Voldemort. That is why we see more characters in the end. Harry is the chosen one, but he still needs the rest to succeed in this quest.

TF-IDF

In this part we are going to explore about TF(term frequency), which is the repetition of a word in an absolute value. Furthermore, we have IDF(Inverse document frequency) which in relative values it measures a repeated word in comparison with the rest of the collection . Finally, TF-IDF is a metric that allow us a real value of a word in a document.

In order to create a TF and a IDF we need the total number of repetition of each word in each book, and the total number of word of each book.

Remember that for TF-IDF, we do not need to remove stop words because they are naturally remove.

#Total repetition of each word by book
hp_words_count <- hp_words_processed |> 
    count(book, word, sort = TRUE)

#Total words by book
hp_total_words <- hp_words_count |> 
  #we group by books to sum all the totals in the n column of book_words
  group_by(book) |> 
  #we create a column called total with the total of words by book
  summarize(total = sum(n))

hp_book_words <- left_join(hp_words_count, hp_total_words) |>

This is the well-known long tail distribution. There is a similar distribution for all books: most words have very low frequencies (on the left) and a few words have very high frequencies (on the right).

Zipf’s law in Harry Potter

This law address that the frequency of a word appearance in a text is inversely proportional to its rank. Each word has a unique rank, the most repeated word has rank 1 and successively. Consequently, the lower the term frequency, it will has a higher rank.

hp_freq_by_rank <- hp_book_words |> 
  group_by(book) |> 
  #we create the column for the rank with row_number
  mutate(rank = row_number()) |> 
  ungroup()

  ggplot(hp_freq_by_rank, aes(rank, term_frequency, color = book)) + 
  #we add a line in the plot with the two coefficients we have found
  geom_abline(intercept = -0.84, slope = -1, 
              color = "gray50", linetype = 2) +
  geom_line(size = 1.1, alpha = 0.8, show.legend = FALSE) + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10()

Using this code, we finally obtain tf-idf. In the book deathly hallows “C” appears. We have checked using this code (grep(“^c\(", hp_words\)word)) in which situations c is used, and it was just an error. Therefore, we remove it in order to not interfere in our analysis.

These first words in the dataframe have very low TF-IDF, near zero, because these are words that occur in many of the documents in a collection.

HP_book_tf_idf_filtered %>%

Meassuring tf-idf show us comparison between texts. One word can be relevant in a document, very representative, but if it occurs a lot in all the books, it will not be distinctive of one.

In our case, in the film Goblet of fire there are some distinctive words like cedric or champions because in this book occurs the championship in which Cedric dies by the hands of Voldemort.

We can see that characters are very meaningful again because in each book there are distinctive characters, for instance Dobby in the Chamber of Secrets or Luna in Order of Phoenix

Finally, we have Horcrux, which is a key word and we could say distinctive from the last to books because in that moment they realized Voldemort only can be defeated by destroying his pieces of soul contained in the Horcrux.

N-grams

In this case we will use 2-grams, so we will se which pair of words are repeated the most. With this code, we prepare the books to be analized by 2-grams.

# Lista de los títulos de los libros de Harry Potter
hp_books <- c(
  "philosophers_stone",

# Combinar los textos en un solo marco de datos y tokenizar en bigramas
hp_words_2_grams <- hp_textos %>%
  # Nombrar cada elemento de la lista
  set_names(hp_books) %>%
  # Convertir cada libro en un marco de datos y combinarlos en un solo marco de datos
  map_df(as_tibble, .id = "book") %>%
  mutate(book = factor(book, levels = hp_books)) %>%
  drop_na(value) %>%
  # Crear una columna de identificación de capítulo
  group_by(book)  %>%
  mutate(chapter = row_number(book))  %>%
  ungroup()  %>%
  # Tokenizar el marco de datos en bigramas
  unnest_tokens(bigram, value, token = "ngrams", n = 2) |> 
  select(-chapter)

hp_words_2_grams <- hp_textos %>%
  # Nombrar cada elemento de la lista
  set_names(hp_books) %>%
  # Convertir cada libro en un marco de datos y combinarlos en un solo marco de datos
  map_df(as_tibble, .id = "book") %>%
  mutate(book = factor(book, levels = hp_books)) %>%
  drop_na(value) %>%
  # Crear una columna de identificación de capítulo
  group_by(book)  %>%
  mutate(chapter = row_number(book))  %>%
  ungroup()  %>%
  # Tokenizar el marco de datos en bigramas
  unnest_tokens(bigram, value, token = "ngrams", n = 2) %>%
  select(-chapter) %>%
  # Añadir nuevamente la columna book
  mutate(book = factor(book, levels = hp_books))
hp_words_2_grams_final <- hp_words_2_grams |> 
  count(bigram, sort = TRUE) |> 
  #we separate each bigram in two columns, word1 and word2
  separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ") |> 
  #we filter all words included in the word column in stop_words
  filter(!word1 %in% custom_stop_words$word) |> 
  filter(!word2 %in% custom_stop_words$word) |> 
  unite(bigram, word1, word2, sep = " ")

To explore about the story, we will filter by the main two houses of Hogwarts: Gryffindor and Slytherin.

word_cors %>%
  #we define a vector for 4 words
  filter(item1 %in% c("gryffindor", "slytherin")) |> 
  #we group by item1
  group_by(item1) %>%
  #we use the first 6 most correlated
  slice_max(correlation, n = 6) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  #we reorder item2 regarding its correlation
  mutate(item2 = reorder(item2, correlation)) %>%
  #we plot
  ggplot(aes(item2, correlation, fill=item1)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  facet_wrap(~ item1, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip()
